To use the quotient rule we first identify the numerator $f(x) = e^{x}$
and the denominator $g(x) = x^{2} -3$. Then we calculate $f'(x) = e^x$
and $g'(x) = 2x$. The rest is a walk in the park, just plug it in:

\begin{align*}
&\frac{d}{dx}\bigg(\frac{e^{x}}{x^{2}-3}\bigg)\\
=& \frac{e^x(x^2-3)-2x(e^x)}{(x^2-3)^2} \\
=& \frac{e^{x}(x^{2}-3 - 2x)}{(x^{2}-3)^{2}}\\
=& \frac{e^{x}(x-3)(x+1)}{(x^{2}-3)^{2}}
\end{align*}
